		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The Mandelbrot and Julia sets use the same formula, but they use C differently.
<br />
<br />The Mandelbrot set use the current complex number (where the pixel coordinates are) for the value of C on every iteration, thus it changes on every pixel.
<br />
<br />Julia sets use one fixed complex number for the value of C on every iteration, thus it remains fixed.  The fixed complex number is supposed to be assigned before rendering the Julia set.
<br />
<br />Since Julia sets use a fixed point and the Mandelbrot set uses every point, it can be said that the Mandelbrot set is an index to every possible Julia set.  I will even go so far as to say the Mandelbrot set *is* every Julia set mashed up together in one fractal universe.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
